<h2>Why Rural States Pay More</h2>
<p>The single biggest predictor of CRNA salary is the degree to which a market depends on CRNAs to deliver anesthesia independently. In states where CRNAs practice without physician supervision — which includes most rural states and many that have opted out of the Medicare supervision requirement — CRNAs function as the sole anesthesia provider. Hospitals in these markets must pay competitively to attract and retain them because there is no cheap backup.</p>
<p>Urban markets with large academic medical centers often pay less because the supply of anesthesiologists is higher, creating more competition and allowing hospitals to use CRNAs in supervised roles with lower autonomy and lower pay.</p>

