<h2>States with Lowest Average CRNA Salaries</h2>
<p>Several states with high anesthesiologist density, physician supervision requirements, or large academic center dominance have lower average CRNA salaries despite high costs of living:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Maryland:</strong> $180,000 - $220,000 — high physician supply near DC, supervision common</li>
<li><strong>New York:</strong> $185,000 - $225,000 — large teaching hospital market, COL very high</li>
<li><strong>New Jersey:</strong> $180,000 - $218,000 — proximity to NYC creates physician competition</li>
<li><strong>Connecticut:</strong> $178,000 - $215,000 — small state, well-staffed urban hospitals</li>
<li><strong>Massachusetts:</strong> $180,000 - $220,000 — major academic medical centers dominate the market</li>
</ul>

<h2>CRNA vs. Anesthesiologist: The Pay Comparison</h2>
<p>Anesthesiologists earn $350,000-$450,000+ on average, compared to $215,000-$240,000 for CRNAs nationally. The gap is real but narrowing in independent practice states. When you factor in the 4-year medical school debt ($250,000-$350,000 average), 4-year residency with resident pay, and delayed career start, the lifetime earnings comparison is much closer than the annual salary gap suggests.</p>
<p>A CRNA practicing independently in a rural market at $300,000+, starting work at 28-30 versus a physician starting at 32-33 with significant debt, accumulates comparable or greater net wealth over a 30-year career in many scenarios.</p>

<h2>CRNA Locum Tenens: The Highest-Earning Path</h2>
<p>Locum tenens CRNAs work short-term contracts at hospitals, surgery centers, and pain management practices that need temporary coverage. Rates in 2026 typically range from $220-$350/hour, with some rural and urgent placements reaching $400+/hour. At 40 hours/week, a locum CRNA earning $280/hour grosses $583,000 annually — before benefits considerations. The trade-off: no paid time off, no health insurance (must purchase independently), and the logistical demands of constant relocation.</p>

<div class="box">
<strong>The geographic strategy:</strong> Many CRNAs work the first 5-10 years in urban markets for training variety and career building, then relocate to rural markets where pay is highest and autonomy is greatest. The combination of urban training depth and rural market premium represents the peak earnings path for most CRNAs willing to relocate.
</div>

